history.content: 128 relies on subjects taught at the end of 120 unfortunately.  Here's the website for 128, spring: http://www-inst.eecs.berkeley.edu/~ee128/sp15/agenda/ .  You can see that right away he expects some understanding of the Laplace Domain & stability, though the lectures seem to review a bit in the beginning.  So if you are willing to maybe do a little catching up in the beginning (there are many resources that you can google), you can do it.

children.subject:
I took 16A/B. They didn't really cover Laplace in those classes...

Would I still be ok? I am taking it with Fearing.

Not sure what 16B covers. Did you do any feedback? Black's law/thm/whatever? Does the phrase "loop gain" mean anything to you? What about phasors? Did you cover how complex exponentials are sinusoids? Or how they're used to solve differential equations?
I'm familiar with all of these things except Black's law?

Black's law states that the gain of a system in negative feedback is the forward gain over 1 + the loop gain. If you covered feedback you probably covered it. I think you'll probably be fine, but I might read ME132 notes if you can get them, or at least read the first few chapters of the 128 textbook first.

As a counterpoint, I took it without 120 (but had ME132). 132 doesn't actually go over Laplace/Z domains specifically (at least, no more than EE20 did) but I was fine for 134. As long as you remember your phasors from 20/40, you'll probably be fine.
So what parts of EE120 are needed in C128 other than Laplace domain/Z domains?
